@mhdempsey @HipCityReg honestly still mad you talked me out of it. the world could really use a mochi vending machine right about now.

@HipCityReg i decided to start Cosmic instead and am happy I did but I sometimes think about what running a wasabi farm in the blue ridge mountains of North Carolina would be like. I think I’ll prob do it some day.

@HipCityReg real wasabi only grows in a few places on earth, mostly in eastern world. when I found that the only climates in NA that could support wasabi farming were parts of Oregon & the blue ridge mountains of NC, i went deep into research and came very close to starting a wasabi farm...

@HipCityReg i found that it was incredibly rare due to difficult growing reqs and short shelf life — it needs shady conditions and only really thrives if left near active streams. Not ideal for sustainable, scalable farming and few places fit it’s needs...

@HipCityReg when i was ~21 y/o and working at a restaurant i realized that the vast majority of wasabi was just colored horseradish and most people had never tried real wasabi so i started to do more research as to why real wasabi was so difficult to find...

@NickLTC Couldn’t agree more! There are a lot of advancements in zero gravity + VR that make me hopeful we’re able to replicate this phenomenal experience for the masses.

If you’re interested in this phenomenon I strongly recommend the short film, “Overview”, documenting astronauts’ life-changing stories of experiencing Earth from the outside.\n\nhttps://t.co/sbcClwKyT6

Apollo 14 astronaut, Edgar Mitchell, described the experience as becoming profoundly aware that each & every atom in the universe was connected in some way — that all the humans, animals and systems were a part of the same thing, a synergistic whole. An “interconnected euphoria”.

It’s been reported that when viewing Earth from space, national boundaries vanish, the conflicts that divide people become less important, and the need to create a more unified society becomes both obvious and imperative.

Common reactions from those that experience “The Overview Effect” are a feeling of awe for the planet, a profound understanding of the interconnection of all life, and a renewed sense of responsibility for taking care of the environment.

“The Overview Effect”, a phrase coined by space philosopher Frank White, refers to the experience of seeing the reality of the Earth in space, which is immediately understood to be a tiny, fragile ball of life, hanging in the void, shielded & nourished by a paper-thin atmosphere. https://t.co/14AO9NTBkr

@toshistack @MattSenter, the Lolli team, & I built a co called Cosmic. It was an e-commerce gateway that let merchants sell their products anywhere. We got acq'd by PopSugar & then again by Ebates. We were on a mission to democratize commerce & have continued on that mission with @trylolli.

It's not that it's easier the second time around. It's still really fucking hard to build anything great.\n\nIt's that you know what to do, you don't make as many mistakes, and you move much much faster.

I've heard a lot of people say that everyone should start a company at least once.

Not sure if I agree with that advice but will say that if you do start a company, you should start at least two.

Cannot even begin to explain how much better it feels the second time around.
